;Patents: Building a system that encourages innovation
Tigezzulin: asebded n unagraw ara yemmudden tabɣest i usnulfu


;Our patent system should work with and for open innovation, not against it.
Anagraw-nneɣ n tgezzulin yesssefk ad ifaṛes tagnitt seg usnulfu yeldin udiɣ ad ittekki deg unegmu-is, maca ur teddu ara mgal-is.


;Patents were designed to create incentive for innovation. But the patent system and software development don’t always get along so well. Software patents are often written so broadly that they’re open to misinterpretation, and exclusive rights can far outlive the shelf life of the software itself. All of which creates obstacles and uncertainty for innovators, and leaves the door open for patent trolls and endless litigation.
Tigezzulin ttwafeṣlen akken ad egent lḥir i usnulfu. Maca, anagraw n tigezzulin akked tneflit n iseɣzanen ur ttemlalen ara tikwal. Tigezzulin n iseɣzanen ttwarunt di ṭaqa n tikwal akken ad eǧǧent yir  agzay akked izerfan i kra n yemdanen kan zemren daɣen ad aɛddin ugar n tenzat n tudert n ufaris s timmad-is. Ayagi meṛṛa yerra tilisa akked ccek i wid yebɣan ad d-snulfun, ig=hi d ayen yeǧǧan tabburt teldi i umennuɣ ɣef izerfan n tigezzulin .


;High Tech patents are the subject of more disputes than all other patents combined.
Tigezzulin ɣef titiknulujiyin tineggura xelqent-d aṭas n wawal ugar n tigezzulin-nniḍen ɣas akken dduklent.


